sfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom"},"zh":{"um 1335–":"大約1335年–歿","1335–Male":"1335年–歿","1337–Female":"1337年–歿","1361–1420":"1361年–1420年","1308–Male":"1308年–歿","1337":"1337年","1335":"1335年","1453":"1453年","1420":"1420年","1361":"1361年","1382":"1382年","1308":"1308年","um 1335":"大約1335年","England":"英國","Gosfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"英國英格蘭艾可格斯費爾德","lifeSummary":"Smith是Smith的兒子，於大約1335年出生在英國。他和Smith至少有1個女兒。"},"zh-hans":{"um 1335–":"大约1335年–殁","1335–Male":"1335年–殁","1337–Female":"1337年–殁","1361–1420":"1361年–1420年","1308–Male":"1308年–殁","1337":"1337年","1335":"1335年","1453":"1453年","1420":"1420年","1361":"1361年","1382":"1382年","1308":"1308年","um 1335":"大约1335年","England":"英国","Gosfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"英国英格兰艾可格斯費爾德","lifeSummary":"Smith是Smith的儿子，于大约1335年出生在英国。他和Smith至少有1个女儿。"},"hr":{"um 1335–":"oko 1335.–preminuo","1335–Male":"1335–preminuo","1337–Female":"1337–preminula","1361–1420":"1361.–1420","1308–Male":"1308–preminuo","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1420":"1420","1361":"1361.","1382":"1382","1308":"1308","um 1335":"oko 1335.","England":"England","Gosfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Gosfield, Essex, Engleska, United Kingdom"},"cs":{"um 1335–":"okolo 1335–Zesnulý","1335–Male":"1335–Zesnulý","1337–Female":"1337–Zesnulá","1361–1420":"1361–1420","1308–Male":"1308–Zesnulý","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1420":"1420","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1308":"1308","um 1335":"okolo 1335","England":"Anglie","Gosfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Gosfield, Essex, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"um 1335–":"omkring 1335–Afdød","1335–Male":"1335–Afdød","1337–Female":"1337–Afdød","1361–1420":"1361–1420","1308–Male":"1308–Afdød","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1420":"1420","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1308":"1308","um 1335":"omkring 1335","England":"England","Gosfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Gosfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"um 1335–":"circa 1335–Overleden","1335–Male":"1335–Overleden","1337–Female":"1337–Overleden","1361–1420":"1361–1420","1308–Male":"1308–Overleden","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1420":"1420","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1308":"1308","um 1335":"circa 1335","England":"England","Gosfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Gosfield, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"um 1335–":"about 1335–Deceased","1335–Male":"1335–Deceased","1337–Female":"1337–Deceased","1361–1420":"1361–1420","1308–Male":"1308–Deceased","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1420":"1420","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1308":"1308","um 1335":"about 1335","England":"England","Gosfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Gosfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Smith","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name denoting a worker in metal, especially iron, such as a blacksmith or farrier, from Middle English <i>smith</i> ‘smith’ (Old English <i>smith</i>, probably a derivative of <i>smītan</i> ‘to strike, hammer’). Early examples are also found in the Latin form   Faber  . Metal-working was one of the earliest occupations for which specialist skills were required, and its importance ensured that this term and its equivalents in other languages were the most widespread of all occupational surnames in Europe. Medieval smiths were important not only in making horseshoes, plowshares, and other domestic articles, but above all for their skill in forging swords, other weapons, and armor. This is also the most frequent of all surnames in the US. It is very common among African Americans and Native Americans (see also 5 below). This surname (in any of the two possible English senses; see also below) is also found in Haiti. See also   Smither  .","English: from Middle English <i>smithe</i> ‘smithy, forge’ (Old English <i>smiththe</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in or by a blacksmith's shop, occupational, for someone who worked in one, or habitational, from a place so named, such as Smitha in King's Nympton (Devon). Compare   Smithey  .","Irish and Scottish: sometimes adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Gobhann</b>, Irish <b>Mac Gabhann</b> ‘son of the smith’. See   McGowan  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Smithe","meanings":["(1997: 115;2007: 306; 2010: NA)","English: variant of   Smith  ."]},{"name":"Smither","meanings":["English (Surrey): occupational name from Middle English <i>smith(i)ere</i>, <i>smeth(i)ere</i> ‘blacksmith’, a derivative of Middle English <i>smithen</i>, <i>smethen</i>, ‘to make (something) in metal, to forge’. Compare   Smith  ."]},{"name":"Smithey","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): from Middle English <i>smithi</i> ‘smithy, forge’ (Old Norse <i>smithja</i>), used either as a topographic name for someone who lived in or by a blacksmith's shop, or an occupational name for someone who worked in one. Compare   Smith   and   Smead  ."]},{"name":"Smyth","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Ronan, Aidan, Brigid, Conor, Eoin, Malachy, Paddy.","English: variant of   Smith  . This form of the surname is particularly common Ireland."]},{"name":"Smythe","meanings":["English (London): variant of   Smith  ."]},{"name":"McGowan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Siobhan, Cormac, Seamus, Aileen, Colm, Eithne, Kieran, Niall, Paddy.","Scottish and Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac (a') Ghobhainn</b> or <b>Mac Gobhann</b> (Scottish) or <b>Mac (an) Ghabhann</b> (Irish), ‘son of (the) smith’. This name has also been Anglicized as   Smith   and   Smithson  ."]},{"name":"Smead","meanings":["English:","occupational name from Middle English <i>smeth(e)</i> ‘smith’, a phonetic variant of   Smith   1 that was widespread in medieval England, especially in south-eastern and south-western counties.","topographic, occupational, and habitational name from Middle English <i>smethe</i> ‘smithy, forge’ (Old English <i>smethe</i>), a side form of   Smith   2, for someone who lived and worked at a blacksmith's, or who lived in or came from a place so named, such as Smeeth (Kent) or Smeed Farm in Hastingleigh (Kent). Compare the synonymous   Smithey  ."]},{"name":"Faber","meanings":["German, Dutch, French (Alsace and Lorraine), and Danish; Slovak and Czech (mainly <b>Fáber</b>): occupational name from Latin <i>faber</i> ‘blacksmith’. At the time of the Reformation, it was much used as a humanistic name, a translation into Latin of vernacular surnames such as German   Schmidt   and Dutch   Smit  . Compare   Fabri   and   Fauber  .","History: In North America, this surname was originally also part of a title. It was François Lefebvre, <i>sieur</i> Duplessis Faber from Paris, France, whose title <i>sieur Duplessis Faber</i> was shortened into the surname <i>Faber</i>. He married Marie-Madeleine Chorel in Champlain, QC, in 1689."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":2,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705195,"age":47,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Smith was born about 1335, in England as the son of Smith. He had at least 1 daughter with Smith."},"et":{"um 1335–":"umbes 1335–Surnud","1335–Male":"1335–Surnud","1337–Female":"1337–Surnud","1361–1420":"1361–1420","1308–Male":"1308–Surnud","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1420":"1420","1361":"1361","1382":"1382"